<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,736,1591]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,880,906]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Recognition.</emphasis>
Small blackish flies (body 
<quantity box="[664,781,880,907]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5–3 mm</quantity>
) (
<figureCitation box="[806,892,880,906]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–72" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,187,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-17@61.[151,1436,181,1725]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 69–72. Platypalpus septentrionalis sp. nov., male. 69. habitus, holotype, lateral view; 70. right epandrial lamella and right cercus, lateral view; 71. epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 72. left epandrial lamella and left cercus, lateral view. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand—epandrium; hypd—hypandrium; rt sur—right surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407035" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407035/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
); palpus pale to pale yellow, whitish pubescent, with short pale hair-like setae (sometimes 1 subapical seta brownish); prothoracic sclerites (except postpronotal lobe) densely silvery grey tomentose, mesopleuron almost entirely shiny, 1 strong npl, 2 broadly set similar sctl, 1 (sometimes 2) strong prescutellar dc; legs almost uniformly brown; halter with yellow knob. Male: mid femur with row of 6–7 closely set black short anteroventral spine-like setae on about basal 1/3 and 2 closely set, moderately long, spine-like setae near extreme base; mid tibia with shallow, ventral subapical excision. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 77–80" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,186,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-20@66.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 77–80. Tachypeza sericeipalpis Frey, male, lateral view. 77. habitus, lateral view; 78. right epandrial lamella, dorsal view; 79. epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 80. left surstylus, lateral view. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand—epandrium; hypd—hypandrium; rt sur—right surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407039/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Figs 78–80</figureCitation>
) large, brown, epandrium shiny. Cerci (
<figureCitation box="[667,748,1096,1122]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–80" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,186,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-20@66.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 77–80. Tachypeza sericeipalpis Frey, male, lateral view. 77. habitus, lateral view; 78. right epandrial lamella, dorsal view; 79. epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 80. left surstylus, lateral view. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand—epandrium; hypd—hypandrium; rt sur—right surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407039/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
) separated, shifted to inner margin of right epandrial lamella; right cercus digitiform, short, with apex slightly extended beyond apex of right epandrial lamella, covered with short setae stronger on inner margin; left cercus short, broad, subrectangular; with some short setae. Hypoproct weakly sclerotized, rather subtriangular, separated from both cerci, bare. Right epandrial lamella (
<figureCitation box="[1253,1335,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–80" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,186,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-20@66.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 77–80. Tachypeza sericeipalpis Frey, male, lateral view. 77. habitus, lateral view; 78. right epandrial lamella, dorsal view; 79. epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 80. left surstylus, lateral view. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand—epandrium; hypd—hypandrium; rt sur—right surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407039/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) without ventral lobe, produced apicoventrally; with cluster of several spine-like short marginal setae apically; right surstylus separated from epandrial lamella, narrow, with two projections, outer projection very short, inner projection long, stylet-like; right bacilliform sclerite with 2 closely set spine-like setae. Left epandrial lamella narrow; with large apodeme; bearing some setulae apically; left surstylus (
<figureCitation box="[782,865,1348,1374]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–80" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,186,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-20@66.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 77–80. Tachypeza sericeipalpis Frey, male, lateral view. 77. habitus, lateral view; 78. right epandrial lamella, dorsal view; 79. epandrium with cerci, dorsal view; 80. left surstylus, lateral view. Abbreviations: cerc—cercus; epand—epandrium; hypd—hypandrium; rt sur—right surstylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407039/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
) large, rather subtriangular (lateral view) but with additional narrow pointed projection dorsally; with short marginal setae apically. Hypandrium hump-backed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,736,1591]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1420,1446]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Distribution.</emphasis>
Holarctic; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Frey in Lundstrom &amp; Frey" authorityYear="1913" box="[477,649,1420,1447]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachypeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericeipalpis">
<emphasis box="[477,493,1421,1446]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[506,649,1420,1446]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">sericeipalpis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a disjunct distribution occurring in Eurasia across the arctic region of 
<collectingCountry box="[182,257,1456,1482]" name="Russia" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Russia</collectingCountry>
from Murmanskaya Province to 
<collectingRegion box="[631,740,1456,1482]" country="Russia" name="Chukotka" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Chukotka</collectingRegion>
(including Wrangel Island) and is found locally in mountains of 
<collectingRegion box="[179,348,1492,1518]" country="Russia" name="Altay" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Altay Republic</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[400,496,1492,1518]" country="Russia" name="Buryatiya" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Buryatia</collectingRegion>
(Shamshev, unpubl. data). In North America, this species is newly recorded from the 
<collectingRegion box="[151,390,1528,1554]" country="Canada" name="Northwest Territories" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Northwest Territories</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[445,541,1529,1555]" country="Canada" name="Nunavut" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Nunavut</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[579,667,1528,1554]" name="Canada" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Canada</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
